The angucycline antibiotics are a large group of naturally occurring aromatic polyketides of microbial origin (11, 15). They exhibit a wide range of biological activities, which include antibacterial, antiviral, antitumor, enzyme inhibitory, and platelet aggregation inhibitory effects. Although all the mem- bers contain a benz[a]anthraquinone skeleton of decaketide origin, their structural diversity is very broad and they have a wide variety of oxidation states. Hatomarubigins A, B, C, and D (Fig. 1) belong to the angucycline family and reverse col- chicine resistance in multidrug-resistant tumor cells (8). Among them, hatomarubigin D is a unique hatomarubigin C dimer with a methylene linkage. Such a dimer has not been reported previously, and little is known about the mechanism of the methylene bridge formation between two aromatic rings. In this study, a gene cluster for hatomarubigin biosynthesis was identiﬁed in Streptomyces sp. strain 2238-SVT4, and a part of the gene cluster was expressed in Streptomyces lividans to pro- duce the hatomarubigins. Bacterial strains, plasmids, and culture conditions. Streptomyces sp. 2238- SVT4 was used for the cloning experiments. The media and growth conditions for Streptomyces sp. 2238-SVT4 were those described previously (8). Streptomyces lividans TK23 (9), Escherichia coli JM110, and the E. coli/Streptomyces shuttle vector pWHM3 (10) were used for expression of the hatomarubigin biosynthesis genes. E. coli XL1-Blue MRF(cid:1) and plasmids pGEM-5Z, pGEM-7Z, pGEM-11Z, pUC118, and pUC119 were used for sequencing analyses.

DNA isolation and manipulation. All restriction enzymes, T4 DNA ligase, and calf intestinal alkaline phosphatase were obtained from Nippon Gene (Toyama, Japan). Transformation of E. coli with plasmid DNA by electroporation was performed under standard conditions using a Gene Pulser II electroporation system (Bio-Rad, Hercules, CA). Other general procedures were performed as described by Sambrook et al. (16). Ampliﬁcation and cloning of aromatase and cyclase genes. Strain 2238-SVT4(cid:1) Takashi Kawasaki, Reiko Hirashima, Tomoka Maruta, Haruka Sato, Ayumi Maeda, Yuki Yamada, Maho Takeda, and Yoichi Hayakawa* Faculty of Pharmaceutical Sciences, Tokyo University of Science, 2641 Yamazaki, Noda, Chiba 278-8510, Japan

Streptomyces sp. strain 2238-SVT4 produces hatomarubigins A, B, C, and D, which belong to the angucycline family. Among them, hatomarubigin D has a unique dimeric structure with a methylene linkage. PCR using aromatase and cyclase gene-speciﬁc primers identiﬁed the hrb gene cluster for angucycline biosynthesis in Streptomyces sp. 2238-SVT4. The cluster consisted of 30 open reading frames, including those for the minimal polyketide synthase, ketoreductase, aromatase, cyclase, O-methyltransferase, oxidoreductase, and oxygenase genes. Expression of a part of the gene cluster containing hrbR1 to hrbX in Streptomyces lividans TK23 resulted in the production of hatomarubigins A, B, and C. Hatomarubigin D was obtained from the conversion of hatomarubigin C by a puriﬁed enzyme encoded by hrbY, among the remaining genes. Received 17 March 2010/Accepted 27 April 2010

The reaction mixture con- sisted of 1(cid:2) GC buffer I (TaKaRa, Kyoto, Japan), 0.4 mM deoxynucleoside triphosphate mixture, 2 (cid:3)M each primer, 0.5 ng/(cid:3)l genomic DNA, and 0.05 U/(cid:3)l LA Taq DNA polymerase (TaKaRa). After heating of the mixture at 95°C for 4 min, PCR was performed for 30 cycles (95°C for 1 min, 50°C for 30 s, 72°C for 45 s). After puriﬁcation with a QIAquick gel extraction kit (Qiagen, Hilden, Germany), the PCR products were linked with the pGEM-T Easy vector (Pro- mega, Madison, WI) by using T4 DNA ligase. E. coli was transformed with the plasmid DNA, and selected clones were used for sequencing analysis. Southern blot analysis of genomic DNA. The DNA fragments used as probes were labeled using an AlkPhos direct labeling kit (GE Healthcare, Piscataway, NJ). Streptomyces sp. 2238-SVT4 genomic DNA was digested with SacI or NotI and run on a 0.7% agarose gel. DNA was transferred to nylon membranes and ﬁxed. After the membranes were incubated with the probes at 65°C for 16 h, the membranes were washed and then developed using an ECF detection module (GE Healthcare). Images were obtained with a FLA2000 image reader (FujiF- ilm, Tokyo, Japan).

Cloning of a gene cluster for hatomarubigin biosynthesis. A cosmid library was constructed from the hatomarubigin producer. Streptomyces sp. 2238-SVT4 genomic DNA was partially digested with Sau3AI and ligated to the pWE15 cosmid vector (Stratagene, La Jolla, CA). The ligated DNAs were packaged using a Gigapack III XL packaging extract (Stratagene) and used to infect E. coli XL1-Blue MRF(cid:1). E. coli colonies obtained by transfection with the cosmids were then screened for the presence of genes encoding aromatase or cyclase by colony hybridization, using the PCR products labeled with the AlkPhos direct labeling kit (GE Healthcare) as probes. Selected positive clones were subsequently ana- lyzed by Southern hybridization with the same probe, and cosmids 37 and 6 were unambiguously found to contain the aromatase and cyclase gene sequences, respectively. Cosmid fragments were selected and sequenced to identify an angucycline biosynthesis gene cluster. DNA sequencer (3100 Genetic Analyzer; Applied Biosystems).

Expression of hatomarubigin biosynthesis genes in S. lividans. Cosmid 6 was digested with BamHI, and a 16-kbp fragment containing hrbR1 to hrbO was ligated with BamHI-digested pBluescript II KS. The plasmid was digested with XbaI and BstBI to give a 13.5-kbp DNA fragment from hrbR1 to a BstBI site (Fig. 2, HR1). A 6.3-kbp DNA fragment from a BstBI site to hrbS (Fig. 2, HR2) was ampliﬁed from Streptomyces sp. 2238-SVT4 genomic DNA using primers with an additional NsiI site (underlined) (5(cid:1)-TCGCATGCCGCCCTGCAGTT CGAACCGGCGGGC-3(cid:1) and 5(cid:1)-TGCATGCATTCACCAGTCCAGCACCTG TCCTTC-3(cid:1)). A 5.2-kbp fragment consisting of hrbT to hrbX (Fig. 2, HR3) was ampliﬁed from the genomic DNA using primers with additional NsiI and HindIII (5(cid:1)-TGCATGCATGTGCGAGAGCGCTGGGACGCACGC-3(cid:1) sites Nucleotide sequencing. To construct a plasmid containing hrbR1 to hrbX (pWHM3-HR), HR1 (13.5 kbp), BstBI/NsiI-digested HR2 (6.3 kbp), NsiI/HindIII-digested HR3 (5.2 kbp), and XbaI/HindIII-digested pWHM3 were ligated and introduced into E. coli. The pWHM3-HR plasmid was selected by digestion with restriction enzymes. pWHM3-HR prepared from E. coli JM110 was introduced into S. lividans TK23. The transformants were cultivated at 27°C for 5 days on a rotary shaker in 200-ml Erlenmeyer ﬂasks containing 30 ml of a medium consisting of soluble starch (2.0%), glucose (0.5%), yeast extract (0.5%; Difco, Detroit, MI), Bacto (cid:1) 7H2O peptone (0.3%; Difco), meat extract (0.3%), KH2PO4 (0.02%), MgSO4 (0.06%), and thiostrepton (10 (cid:3)g/ml) (pH 7.2 before sterilization). The hrbY gene (1.1 kbp) was ampliﬁed from the genomic DNA using primers with additional BamHI and HindIII sites (underlined) (5(cid:1)-CGCGGATCCAGTGCAACAGTCGCGGT CGTCGGC-3(cid:1) and 5(cid:1)-ACCAAGCTTTCAGCCGGCGGTGGGACCGAACT G-3(cid:1)). BamHI/HindIII-digested pQE30 and hrbY were ligated and introduced into E. coli M15, which was cultured in 500-ml Erlenmeyer ﬂasks containing 100 ml of LB medium with kanamycin (25 (cid:3)g/ml) and ampicillin (100 (cid:3)g/ml). After isopropyl-(cid:4)-D-thiogalactopyranoside (0.1 mM) was added, the culture was incu- bated at 18°C for 20 h on a rotary shaker. The cells were washed with 50 mM Tris-HCl (pH 7.0)–5 mM dithiothreitol and suspended in 10 ml of the same solution, followed by sonication on ice. The extract was centrifuged and the supernatant was applied to a nickel-nitrilotriacetic acid agarose (Qiagen) column equilibrated with 50 mM Tris-HCl (pH 7.0), 10 mM imidazole, and 5 mM dithiothreitol. The column was washed with 50 mM Tris-HCl (pH 7.0), 20 mM imidazole, and 5 mM dithiothreitol and was then eluted with 50 mM Tris-HCl (pH 7.0), 250 mM imidazole, and 5 mM dithiothreitol. This fraction showed a single band at 40 kDa on SDS-PAGE (15%). The protein concentration was determined with a protein assay kit (Bio-Rad).

Hatomarubigin C was isolated from the culture of Streptomyces sp. 2238-SVT4 as described previously (8) and was used as a substrate for the enzyme reaction. The reaction mixture (500 (cid:3)l) consisted of 50 (cid:3)M hatomarubigin C, 0.2 mg/ml puriﬁed HrbY protein, 2 mM methylcobalamin, 5 mM NADPH, 5 mM MgCl2, 15% dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO), and 100 mM Tris-HCl (pH 7.0). After the mixture was allowed to stand at 30°C for 14 h, the solution was extracted with ethyl acetate, followed by evaporation of the organic layer. The residue was dissolved in 150 (cid:3)l of DMSO and analyzed by HPLC (YMC Pak R-ODS-7 column; YMC) with 88% methanol at a ﬂow rate of 1.0 ml/min. Absorption peaks for hatomarubigins were detected at 470 nm, and conversion rates were calculated from the peak areas. Nucleotide sequence accession number. The nucleotide sequences reported here have been deposited in the GenBank, DDBJ, and EMBL databases under accession number AB524586 (hrb gene cluster).

Ampliﬁcation of angucycline biosynthesis genes from Strep- tomyces sp. 2238-SVT4. Angucycline biosynthesis gene clusters commonly contain both aromatase and cyclase genes, which construct the tetracyclic angucycline frameworks (see Fig. 5). PCR primers were designed from the conserved amino acid sequences of the aromatase (lanL, jadD, and urdL) and cyclase (lanF, jadI, and urdF) genes in the landomycin producer S. cyanogenus S136 (19), the jadomycin producer S. venezuelae ISP5230 (3, 7), and the urdamycin producer S. fradiae Tu¨2717 (4, 6). PCR ampliﬁcation of Streptomyces sp. 2238-SVT4 genomic DNA using these primers gave putative aromatase and cyclase gene fragments. The fragments encoded proteins that shared amino acid identity of 79% with the aromatase UrdL and 76% with the cyclase JadI, respectively. Southern hybridization of genomic DNA with angucycline biosynthesis genes. Streptomyces sp. 2238-SVT4 genomic DNA was digested with NotI or SacI. The digested DNA in agarose gels was subjected to Southern hybridization to identify aro- matase and cyclase genes. Single bands of 8.6 kbp (NotI) and 4.6 kbp (SacI) were hybridized with the aromatase and cyclase gene fragments, respectively, suggesting that the strain con- tained a single set of genes for angucycline biosynthesis.

Cloning of a gene cluster for angucycline biosynthesis from Streptomyces sp. 2238-SVT4. Two cosmid clones were selected from a cosmid library by colony hybridization and Southern blot analysis using the aromatase and cyclase gene fragments as probes. Nucleotide sequencing identiﬁed genes encoding putative aromatase, phosphopantetheinyl transferase, and ox- ygenase genes in a 3.8-kbp BamHI fragment from cosmid 37. A 4.6-kbp SacI fragment from cosmid 6 contained genes homol- ogous to cyclase, ketosynthase, and chain length determinant APPL. ENVIRON. MICROBIOL. factor genes. Expression of a part of the hrb gene cluster in S. lividans. To establish the function of the hrb genes, the expression plasmid pWHM3-HR containing hrbR1 to hrbX was constructed (Fig. 2) and introduced into S. lividans TK23. The transformant bearing pWHM3-HR or an empty vector (pWHM3) was cul- tivated, and the mycelial extract was analyzed by HPLC. S. lividans expressing the hrb genes produced hatomarubigins A, B, and C and rubiginone B2 (Fig. 3), although no peak corre- sponding to hatomarubigin D was detected. These results es- carrier protein, ketoreductase, aromatase, tablished that the hrb genes construct a gene cluster for hato- marubigin biosynthesis in Streptomyces sp. 2238-SVT4. Conversion of hatomarubigin C into hatomarubigin D by the hrbY gene product. Among the remaining genes, hrbY was selected as a primary candidate for methylene bridge forma- tion because it existed inside hrbR3, which revealed similarity to jadR1, a regulator of angucycline biosynthesis (18). The putative oxidoreductase HrbY was expressed in E. coli, and the puriﬁed protein was tested for its ability to convert hatomaru- bigin C. The substrate was converted into hatomarubigin D by HrbY using methylcobalamin and NADPH as cofactors (Fig. 4). No reaction was observed when S-adenosylmethionine was used instead of methylcobalamin. The conversion rate (32.3%) was decreased when the redox cofactor was replaced by NADH (8.0%), NADP(cid:5) (2.7%), or NAD(cid:5) (2.1%). These re- sults identiﬁed HrbY as a novel enzyme that catalyzes the methylene bridge formation between two angucycline mole- cules.

A 35-kbp DNA fragment containing aromatase and cyclase genes was sequenced to identify the hatomarubigin biosynthe- sis gene cluster in Streptomyces sp. 2238-SVT4. The region consisted of 33 ORFs, including minimal polyketide synthase, ketoreductase, aromatase, and cyclase genes, which are com- monly found in angucycline biosynthesis gene clusters. Two primary metabolic genes (S-adenosylmethionine synthase and carbohydrate kinase) existed at one end of the fragment. The other end encoded an alanine-rich uncharacterized Streptomy- ces protein. Thus, 30 ORFs were designated hrb genes as can- didates for the hatomarubigin biosynthesis gene cluster. Since a fragment from hrbR1 to hrbX contained the genes necessary for angucycline biosynthesis, this region was ex- pressed in S. lividans to establish the function of the hrb genes. The products of the transformant indicated that these genes are sufﬁcient for the biosynthesis of all hatomarubigins except hatomarubigin D.

The hrbI gene resembles lanV, a 6-ketoreductase gene in landomycin biosynthesis (12), and is assignable to the same function (Fig. 5). The hrbU gene is a candidate for an O- methyltransferase gene from its homology to tcmO, an O- methyltransferase gene in tetracenomycin biosynthesis (17). An hrbG homologous gene, lndM2, is responsible for 6-hy- droxylation in landomycin biosynthesis (20), suggesting that HrbG catalyzes the 6-hydroxylation of rubiginone B2 to yield hatomarubigin A (Fig. 5). In landomycin biosynthesis, the two tandem genes lanZ4 and lanZ5 encoding oxidoreductase and oxygenase, respectively, are involved in 11-hydroxylation (14). A lanZ5 homologous gene hrbX is followed by the reductase gene hrbW. These two gene products might catalyze the 11- hydroxylation of rubiginone B2 to give hatomarubigin B (Fig. 5). The hrb cluster includes three putative regulatory genes. HrbR1, HrbR2, and HrbR3 show sequence similarity with a putative regulatory protein (SCP1.58c/295) of Streptomyces coelicolor (2), a MarR-family regulator (SACE_0419) of Sac- charopolyspora erythraea (13), and an atypical response regu- lator (JadR1) of Streptomyces venezuelae (18), respectively. The puriﬁed protein encoded by hrbY converted hatomaru- bigin C into hatomarubigin D in the presence of methylcobal- APPL. ENVIRON. MICROBIOL. enzyme; (C) reaction mixture with HrbY.

Since the reaction required NAD(P)H but not FAD, the recombinant enzyme might be puriﬁed as a complex with FAD. The enzyme used methylcobalamin as a C1 donor for the methylene bridge formation. Although methylcobalamin participates in several enzymatic methyl group transfer reactions (1), no similarity is found between HrbY and such enzymes. The enzymatic hato- marubigin C conversion reported here should greatly facilitate future investigations to clarify the exact mechanism of this unique methylene bridge formation. ous gift of plasmids and E. coli strains.
